@Oli - With a regular user account the malware can also set it up to startup during the login, it will never go away. From a practical perspective it can spread and become resident just as it would with a root account.
I really don't see much advantage of a malware to have root privileges on a single user system. 
The user issue is not OS technically related, there were plenty of other distributions where the users quickly moved to a root account to have "full" control of their system. Ubuntu's adoption of sudo by default was a good decision IMHO.

@Daniel:
Ubuntu One only works with Ubuntu/Linux, no MAC client, no Windows client, no Android client (that I've seen). And I have several machines with both operating systems on it that I need to sync files with. Until Ubuntu One syncs with multiple OSs I won't be using it.
